@mehrdada 

It would be great to add support for a middleware pipeline similar to aspcore (see https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/middleware) or expressjs.  That way it would be easy to build plugins and customization on top of the c# gRPC framework.  I see the Go version of the library already has this essentially with their interceptor implementation.

As it is I'm having to re-use a bunch of boilerplate code (JWT token validation, logging, custom exception handling, etc) for each rpc endpoint.

@mehrdada 

I hacked together an example regarding what functionality I was looking for at https://github.com/plaisted/grpc-csharp-middleware

I only implemented it for `UnaryServerCallHandler` for a demo but would be simple to extend the concept to the others as well. With the streaming request or response I'm guessing it'd only make sense the have the middleware execute at the beginning and end of the transmission. Executing for every item in the stream seems like overkill.

Anyway the basic idea is that you can create a middleware pipeline like:
```csharp
var pipeline = new PipelineBuilder();
```

you can then add a middleware to the pipeline (delegate in this example although the POC in the repo allows middleware classes to be used as well):
```csharp
pipeline.Use(async (ctx, next) =>
{
    Console.WriteLine(ctx.Request.ToString()); //executed on the request path
    await next(ctx); //continue to next item in pipeline (main RPC function in this case)
    Console.WriteLine(ctx.Response.ToString()); //executed on the return path
});
```

and configure the server to use pipeline on startup:
```csharp
Server server = new Server
{
    MiddlewarePipeline = pipeline.Build(),
    //rest of server config...
};
```

Then when the RPC is called the middleware is executed and the output is seen on console:
```json
{ "name": "you" }
{ "message": "Hello you" }
```

I also added a simple `Dictionary<string, object>` called `Items` to the `ServerCallContext`.  This allows a middleware to pass objects to the actual RPC function. It would allow scenarios where a plugin authenticates a user and adds the user object to the Items dictionary like:
```csharp
//GRPC request handler
public override Task<HelloReply> SayHello(HelloRequest request, ServerCallContext context)
{
    var user = context.Items.GetUser(); //GetUser() is extension method
    if (user?.HasClaim("Admin"))
    {
        //do admin
    } else
    {
        //reject
    }
    return Task.FromResult(new HelloReply { Message = "Hello " + request.Name });
}
```

Let me know what you think of this direction.

Just found this - this is **GREAT** work.

Let me know if I can do anything to help get this PR in ASAP. I'll be testing it :).

I would suggest using interfaces versus the WrapClass implementation to determine a request/response versus passing in await _call.  Reason being is it's error prone creating middleware ATM, (ensuring that you do include the proper construction) and you can currently throw in any class as middleware without the right responses and there's a lot of reflection going on per call which can be 100% static to keep performance up.

sudo code as follows:

```
public class TestMiddleWare : IResponseMiddleWare, IRequestMiddleWare
{
    void OnRequest(Context);
    void OnResponse(Context);
}

// Additionally the below would add an auto "where" clause since we know what response types we are looking for.

public class TestSpecificResponse : IResponseMiddleWare<HelloRequest>
{
    void OnResponse(Context<HelloRequest> context);
}
```

Also would suggest direct method passing for use when:

```
UseWhen<TestMiddleWare>(myServerImpl.Method);
```

Additionally, is there a plan for client middlewhere? I can def help if not in progress yet.

If this is something you agree with, I can do a pull request on the grpc-csharp-middlewhere for you in the next day or two. If this doesn't make sense, let me know and I can also make a POC for you.
